"Now, Mr. Sherlock Holmes," said the lady as we entered a well-lit dining-room, upon the table of
which a cold supper had been laid out, "I should very much like to ask you one or two plain
questions, to which I beg that you will give a plain answer."

"Certainly, madam."

"Do not trouble about my feelings. I am not hysterical, nor given to fainting. I simply wish to hear
your real, real opinion."

"Upon what point?"

"In your heart of hearts, do you think that Neville is alive?"